        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Test conditions must match CFD boundary conditions within stated tolerances. Flow rate agreement ±2%, speed agreement ±0.5%, hematocrit ±5% relative. All tolerances met; calibration certificates on file."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "rationale": "Hemolysis index predictions compared against in-vitro measurements using normalized index of hemolysis (NIH). Mean absolute percentage error 8.3%; all 5 operating points within 15% of measured NIH. Comparison accounts for combined experimental and numerical uncertainty.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Model predictions must fall within 20% of experimental NIH values at all operating points, accounting for combined uncertainty. Achieved maximum deviation 14.7%; mean deviation 8.3%. Criterion satisfied."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "rationale": "The primary QoI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) is the direct clinical surrogate for red blood cell damage and is the regulatory-accepted metric for hemolysis assessment per ISO 10993-4. The QoI directly maps to the device acceptance criterion without intermediate transformation.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/qoi-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "QoI must be directly traceable to the clinical endpoint (hemolysis) and must be the metric used in the regulatory submission. NIH satisfies both requirements per ISO 10993-4 and FDA guidance on hemolysis testing."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "rationale": "Validation activities performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump — the same geometry class as the VAD device. Operating conditions span the clinical use envelope. Blood analogue fluid properties matched to clinical blood properties within documented tolerances.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/val-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Validation geometry must share key hemodynamic similarity parameters (Reynolds number, specific speed) with the clinical device. Validation operating points must cover the clinical use envelope. Both criteria confirmed by similarity analysis report Rev. C."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence monitored via residual drop of 6 orders of magnitude for continuity and momentum equations. Mass imbalance <0.01% at steady state. Time-averaged quantities sampled over 10 impeller revolutions after initial transient decay.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/solver-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical solver error acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Residuals must drop minimum 5 orders of magnitude; mass imbalance <0.1%; QoI variation <0.5% over final 5 averaging windows. All criteria met at all 5 operating points."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Simulation setup reviewed by independent CFD analyst not involved in the primary analysis. Boundary condition specification, turbulence model selection, and hemolysis model coefficient assignment verified against documented simulation plan. Two discrepancies identified and corrected prior to production runs.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/use-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Use error acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Independent technical review of simulation setup required prior to production runs. Review must cover boundary conditions, model selection, and post-processing scripts. Review completed and documented in Technical Review Record TRR-2025-11-04."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "rationale": "SST k-ω turbulence model selected based on published benchmark studies for confined rotating flow. Power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen et al., modified by Heuser & Opitz) validated against literature datasets. Model form uncertainty estimated via comparison of three turbulence model variants; spread <12% on NIH predictions.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-form",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model form acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Turbulence model selection must be justified by benchmark evidence for geometrically similar flows. Hemolysis model must be validated against at least two independent datasets. Model form uncertainty spread across candidate models must be reported and incorporated into total uncertainty budget."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "rationale": "All model inputs (geometry, fluid properties, boundary conditions, hemolysis model coefficients) sourced from traceable measurements or published literature with documented uncertainty. Monte Carlo UQ propagates input uncertainty distributions through the model to QoI uncertainty bounds.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model inputs acceptance criteria",
        "description": "All inputs must have documented sources and uncertainty estimates. UQ must propagate input uncertainties to QoI. 95th-percentile NIH including input uncertainty must remain below clinical threshold. Satisfied: 95th-percentile NIH = 0.0031 g/100L vs. threshold 0.008 g/100L."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "In-vitro hemolysis experiments conducted on n=5 independent pump specimens across 5 operating points (25 total test runs). Specimen-to-specimen variability quantified; coefficient of variation <8% for NIH across specimens. Sample size justified by power analysis targeting 80% power to detect 20% NIH difference.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/test-samples",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test samples acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Minimum 3 independent specimens required; specimen variability must be characterized and reported. Power analysis or equivalent justification for sample size required. All criteria met: n=5 specimens, CV<10%, power analysis documented in Test Plan TP-2025-08."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Equivalency of input parameters' factor addresses scenarios in which the validation activity is conducted on a surrogate geometry or under surrogate operating conditions that differ from the COU, requiring a formal equivalency argument to bridge the gap between validation domain and deployment domain. In this assessment, the validation experiments were conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry used as the basis for the CFD model, under operating conditions that directly span the five clinical use points without geometric scaling, fluid substitution, or parameter mapping. Because no surrogate or analogue substitution was made — the validation geometry IS the model geometry, and the validation operating points ARE the COU operating points — there is no parametric gap requiring equivalency demonstration. Applying this factor would be vacuous: the equivalency ratio for all parameters is unity by construction. This determination is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 5.3, which scopes the equivalency factor to cases where 'the validation activity differs from the COU in geometry, scale, fluid, or operating regime.' None of those conditions obtain here. The factor is therefore designated not-applicable for this assessment and this COU."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/vad-cou2-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 12 assessed credibility factors achieve levels meeting or exceeding required levels for MRL 5. The single not-applicable factor (Equivalency of input parameters) is properly scoped out with documented rationale: validation was conducted on the identical geometry under identical operating conditions, rendering equivalency demonstration vacuous. Monte Carlo UQ confirms 95th-percentile hemolysis index (0.0031 g/100L) remains well below the clinical threshold (0.008 g/100L) across all 5 operating points. Independent technical review confirmed simulation setup integrity. The credibility evidence, taken in aggregate, provides sufficient confidence that the CFD hemolysis predictions are fit for the intended regulatory use as the primary basis for hemolysis acceptance of the Class III VAD device.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
